AB  - In addition to the theory of comparative advantage and the theory of economies of scale with product differentiation, this paper formalizes a third reason of trade, namely the differences in nonrenewable resource endowments of two trading parties. The paper also examines the division of the gains in trade in a dynamic bargaining framework which requires consistent action by both bargaining parties. A contribution of this paper is to provide a special case under which dynamic bargaining results in efficient resource utilization in bilateral trade.
